<br>
<br>
With that being said, and remember this is my experiences only... The Paladin, in post lvl 30 play, should never be the main tank. The paladin is to assist the main tank and deal as much damage as he can without gaining the aggro off the main. That means the Paladin should never taunt when assisting the main. When a MOB aggros on to a caster, especially the Cleric or Shaman, it is the Paladins job, not the main tanks, to taunt the MOB off the caster long enough for it to be rooted, snared, mezzed, or taken back by the main tank. Belive it or not, but the Paladin IS a very effective taunter! As for the Paladins healing abilities, as weak as they may be, is best used between pulls, not during the battle, so as to let the Cleric/Shaman medd up for the next fight. The Paladins shining moment comes when fighting the undead!!! Unfortunately, that still wasn't enough to keep me playing one . <p></p><span class=m><i></i></span><hr size=1><span class=m> Posts: <b>6</b>  </span></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ubagumntagum.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bagumntagum</A> </span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> </td><td valign=top width=80% class=m><span class=title>   Re: I need a couple of questions answered</span><br><span class=m><font color=#778899>Posted: 10/17/01 12:00:04 pm</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>   &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/febonmoonfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=47.topic&index=3><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/reply.gif border=0 width=20 height=20 alt="reply to this message" align=absmiddle></a>   <hr size=1> Well not to disagree with you Kel, but more of a clarification on what you listed. First off, just because you melee does not make you a tank. There is only 1 true tank in the game and that is a Warrior. A Warrior gets the best bonuses to defense and can take the beating the longest, and that is what a true tank is. As you have noted Fae (I think it was you that posted about the healing in the Raid section? or was it Cen?) that when Bel was tanking, he seemed to take much less damage then when a Ranger got the agro switched to him. This is what makes a tank a tank. Not the ability to do damage, as everyone knows that monks do the most damage output in the game over time, but are not considered tanks (though because they are the best pullers usually at least have the starting agro on them, so they can defend themselves but still not like a warrior). 2nd to the Warrior is Shadow Knight's and Pally's. These 2 classes are equal in that regard as one is not better then the other in tanking, but in a pinch can take over for a warrior and still live longer then any other class. That is it for tanks. All other melee based classes are not tanks. That isn't to say that they can't do their fair share of damage, but again damage delivered to an NPC is not what makes a tank a tank. This does have one exception and that is level. For example in Sol A I was in a group with Vear, Serthi, and Can. A level 47 Monk, 35 Warr, and a 33 Warr. Now if we were all the same level then the tanking rights would be 1st and 2nd the 2 Warriors, then me and then Vear, though Vear as main puller would have to hold his own till the Warriors could taunt the pull off him. But since we were not the same level, Vear was actually the main tank, then Serthi, then Can, and finally me. The 12 level difference between them changes the rules, but this was a specific instance. Also this would lead to a quick explanation of taunting. First and foremost when in a group, there should only be one person taunting. If the puller is a monk then he should only get the MoB mad enough at them just to pull. Once pulled back to the group, the only person that should be taunting is the primary tank. If the puller is taking major damage and fading fast, then secondary tank and if there is a 3rd, should all taunt just to get agro off the puller, but that is the only time they should taunt unless of course the main tank is just taking too much damage and the healer is oom. The reason is so that the MoB never changes direction, this is very important as you will see as you keep reading.<br>
<br>
Now this being said, that does not mean that having all of the other melee classes in your group is worthless. As I said, a tank is not defined as anyone who is melee, but as someone who can take the beating the longest. But the other melee based characters have a major bonus to attack strength. A ranger with 2 good weapons, double attack, and kick has a chance of doing 5 hit's per round! Use this to the groups advantage, as where can you do the most damage and land the most hit's to a MoB? From the back. When you are hitting the MoB from the back, you get an attack bonus and land more hits more often. If you get the agro and tank (now your hitting the MoB from the front) then you can't do as much damage plain and simple. Let's use as an example a 6 person group consisting of 1 Monk (puller), 1 Warrior (main tank), 1 Rogue, 1 Wizard, 1 Ranger, and 1 Cleric. Here is how the pull should go. First the Monk FD pulls so that only 1 MoB is following them. Once back to the group, the Warrior should have already targeted the Monks pull, and everyone should Assist the Warrior (not the Monk, if they pulled more then one MoB, this is very important so that you do not split the agro, as usually the Warrior will taunt the ADD mob first so that it doesn't go off an attack the Wizzy or Cleric). Once everyone is assisting the Warrior, if the Warrior doesn't get the agro soon enough, the Monk can FD to wipe all agro and the Warrior should pick it up and take over. While all this is happening, the Rogue and Ranger are moving to the opposite side of the Warrior to get to the back of the MoB, and actually should not be hitting while doing this so that Warrior is sure to have the most agro. Once they are behind the MoB, that's when the fun begins, because now the damage starts to happen. At this point now that all the Melee have engaged, then Wizzy is free to let fly and nuke as the hate list has a few people ahead of them (don't go crazy cause the DD spells do more damage quicker then melee does, but I don't have to tell a Wizzy that). Of course the Cleric should heal as needed through out this entire process, however, make sure that you do not heal the Monk too soon as that could change agro over to you rather then the Warrior and that is the quickest way to make a bad pull even worse. It's better to have the puller die (sorry Monk) then the entire group. This is just one type of group, and having an enchanter in the mix changes everything (and is a completely different looooong post in itself).<br>
<br>
Okay, so where do SK's and Pallys fall into the mix? Well first you should know what they are. A Shadow Knight is a mix of a Warrior (hence why they are tanks as well) and Necromancers. This makes for an interesting mix, first they do have the ability to somewhat heal themselves (through life taps) and they don't have to target themselves to do this, plus the NPC takes damage at the same time as a life tap takes health from the NPC and gives it to the Shadow Knight. Besides this, they have some nasty DoT's including one that can snare (though to a lesser degree then the actual snare spell). Put all this together combined with taunting and truthfully no one can out taunt an SK not even a Warrior because all of the SK's spells add agro. This doesn't mean that an SK should tank over a Warrior, however, if an ADD jumps on your Wizzy or Cleric, if you have an SK in the group he should be the first and only one to break away from the main pull to go help the Wizzy or Cleric (or healer in general) and all others should remain on the main pull. Oh yeah... note to wizzy's and clerics... DON'T RUN... we have to cast spells and use the taunt skill to get them off you within 1 Round (yes I can get them off you in 1 Round <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ). Taunt has a very short range and won't work if we aren't right next to the mob, however, if we run then we can't cast spells. So if you run, you die... stand still and only lose 2-3 bubbles of health at maximum. Also, don't heal others or attack the MoB... that only makes them madder at you and makes it harder for us to taunt them off you. As for the Pally, they are a mix of Warrior (again... tank) and Clerics. So yes, then can heal, does that mean that they should? No. They should be the very last choice for heals (other then their Lay Hands Complete Heal which if a pull is going sour, should be used to save the main tank so that things can have a chance of changing for the better). Why if they are part Cleric do I say they shouldn't heal? Simple, they are Warriors first. If the Cleric, Druid, or Shaman (whoever is main healer, and in some cases Secondary healer) are oom, and there is a Ranger in the group... the Ranger should break away from the fight and heal. Do the rangers have as good of a heal as the Pally's? Well no... but if the Main tank dies, and the Ranger is still fighting while the Pally is healing, then guess who is going to tank now. If the pull went so bad that the Main tank died, do you really think the Ranger has a chance of living that long? If the Main tank dies and the Pally gets the agro, the Ranger has a much better chance of keeping the Pally alive long enough to kill the MoB, and even let the main healer med up a bit so that the Ranger can jump back in. Besides this the pally can heal himself as well to help the Ranger, where as if the Ranger was tanking the combined heal's of the pally and the Ranger would be less then the damage the Ranger would be taking. And yes Pallys and SK's are exactly the same when it comes to tanking, so if you have a cleric and a necro in the group but no Warrior, then flip a coin as to who is main and who is secondary tank.<br>
<br>
Shamans are a totally different kind of class, and I think one of our Shamans could describe themselves better then I can as I have yet to play a Shaman. Though to put it simply, they are great buffers, and can be main healers as well, and can even replenish their mana quicker by converting health to mana and this is when a pally comes in handy, as they can spend their mana on healing the Shaman while the Shaman converts it to mana. I did this with Gumil in Sol A when he was oom after a long fight.. even though I don't have a heal I can take my health and give it to others. It was a small help, but still a help. They also have nice DoT's and Debuffs (like Kel said) and can really round out a group quite nicely.<br>
<br>
As for Rogues, well Blackpoint can really say it better, and if you read what she wrote in the Newbie section on Rogues, you will really understand Rogues better. And to quote her &quot;A rogue isn't a tank. Repeat, you are not a tank.  It is really hard to solo as a rogue because of your low HP’s.  Stamina boosts are important but a rogue wasn't designed to take a beating.  We can deal the greatest amount of damage in a span of 8 seconds (4 attacks + Riposte + Backstab) but we can't take a lot of punishment.&quot; This is just a small part of what a rogue is, but explains a lot. Check out what else she says as it is very well written.<br>
<br>
And bards, well these are the most interesting classes in Norrath. They have the ability to do damage like a wizard, DoT like a Shaman, Heal like a Cleric, recharge mana like an Enchanter, and fight like a Ranger. Now this is not to say that they can replace any of these other classes as they can only do all this at a much lesser degree. Also notice that I didn't say Warrior, that's because they take damage like a ranger. Worse yet, they don't get double attack, so they can't even deal as much damage out. To make matters worse, most of their spells are group based, so healing 6 players builds up much more agro then healing one even though the heal is much weaker then even a Rangers heal. A bard can &quot;spin&quot; songs which means they sing up to 3 (though I've heard of really experienced bards sing 4 at a time) songs at a time doing damage, healing, and giving strength to the group (an example, as there are many combo's). This will create a great deal of agro, as during this the bard can attack the MoB with a weapon while they do this. Unlike magic, a bard can sing and attack almost at the same time (almost because if you start your song while you are supposed to attack, you will miss the round). This is not to say that bards are not good in groups, it's just that if you don't understand how to play a bard, you will die... a lot. In fact there is much much much more to a bard, and a well played bard can be invaluable to a group, especially as an get out of trouble free card giving instant SoW (well Selo's Accelerando) to everyone in the group, provided you remain near the bard you can all outrun the MoB(s) to safety.<br>
<br>
Now considering I have just written a novel (see what happens when you take a few days off from posting) I will stop here. If you've actually read through this long post then feel free to tell me I'm wrong as this is mostly my opinion from playing these different classes and grouping with them.<br>
