<br>
The short answer -- but this would vary depending on the sham's level -- for the typical camp type group, our role is:<br>
<br>
slow mobs<br>
sow the puller (everybody if the camp is risky)<br>
haste the tanks (lacking enchanter)<br>
buff tank HPs  (lacking cleric)<br>
buff tank AC    (  &quot;       &quot;     )<br>
buff tank stamina and agi <br>
buff other stats if requested<br>
cast heals and regen <br>
dot (if not a short fight)<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
To ramble:<br>
<br>
<br>
You know that one about 'jack-of-all-trades master of none'... that's us, the shamen.  To be even more vauge, our role changes a lot depending on what's on the hunt menu, how fast the group is killing things and what classes are in the group.  And the role of the Shaman also changes as he gets older and has access to new types of spells Upto about level 20 we'll often mix it up in melee, tossing in a dot or two and a heal where needed.  Between 20 and 30ish we go though a bit of a lull, yet to have a our haste spells or our pet, and having weak slows.  We're no longer meleeing but our contribution to groups and ability to solo is a bit weaker that at our other levels.  As soon as we get regen and cannibalize, you'll often find us doing the canni dance, swaping hit points for mana and then regening up.  After about level 35 get their first pet and strong slows and we start come into our own.   <br>
<br>
Probably our most useful and class defining role, especially after our early levels and with mobs that have a lot of HP, is to slow mobs.  A slow mob means that tanks take less damage and live longer, healers have more mana, and the group will need less down time.  <br>
<br>
That said, it's not always worthwhile to slow things.  With low HP mobs, where no fight lasts more than a few rounds, or if you're rooting and dotting things to death, the mana is better spent elsewhere.  <br>
<br>
Aside from slow, we have two other debuffers: the malise series which lowers magic resistances and another spell line that lowers a mob's attack rating.  I hear malise sees a lot of action on raids and such, when it gets harder to make your spells stick, but the attack debuffs don't often get used in my experience.<br>
<br>
Buffs.  Slowing and buffing are what we're know for.  <br>
<br>
The best stat buffs we have are stamina and agility.  The stam buff adds HP and agi will add a few points of AC.  The agi isn't a major AC increase, so depending on how much mana is being spent elsewhere, it might not be worthwhile.  Some shaman also routinely buff str for tanks.  Extra str helps lets you carry more weight without it effecting your AC or running speed and it can add to your max possible damage (if you're already at the damage cap for your weapon at your level it won't).  <br>
<br>
Dex and Charisma see less action.  Dex increases the proc rate on proc'ing weapons and can help a bard miss less notes.  It also very slightly increases the rate at which you'll get weapon skill increases.  Charisma gets you a slightly better deal with vendors, and again helps bards play their songs.  Enchanters benifit from char, but they have their own buff for it, which, depending on their level, might be better.  <br>
<br>
Overall stat buffs don't make <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> that</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> much difference.  They likely won't make an encounter doable if it wasn't before.  They do look good tho <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Aside from the stat buffs, we have a series of HP, AC and haste buffs.  These are pretty high up on our to-do list, but clerics HP and AC buffs are better (as often are an int caster's self-only buffs) and enchanters have a better haste, so if they're in the group those roles will be theirs.  The haste buffs don't last as long as others buffs so if there are serval tanks to haste this can take a lot of shaman's mana.<br>
<br>
Rounding out the buffage are the resistance buffs, which  come out when fighting casting mobs.<br>
<br>
Besides the buffing and debuffing the other spells we'll likely use are healing and regen, nukes and dots, and root.  Root will do in a pinch for crowd control if you don't have an enchanter.  Our dots are pretty good and when soloing and at the earlier levels we use them a lot.  Our healing becomes less effective the higher we level, but it's not until the real high level game that they become almost worthless.<br>
<br>
Finally, there are the utility spells: shrink, sow, levitate, ultravision, see invis, bind, etc.<br>
<br>
Buffer/de-buffer, sow'er, kinda healer, root ghetto-mez'er, dotter and nuker... and Stuff (tm), that's us, shamen.  <br>
